      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Everglades in Peril'' (editorial, April 21):</p>
        <p>According to scientists, much and perhaps all of this ecosystem is vulnerable to a rise in the sea level from global warming.</p>
        <p>In a hundred years, the $7.8 billion plan to restore the Everglades may be seen as a shortsighted boondoggle if it is not accompanied by meaningful reductions in greenhouse gas emissions.</p>
        <p>What is striking is the failure of scientists and policy analysts to raise this point publicly.</p>
        <p>The problem, I suspect, is that this would mean pointing fingers not just at the sugar industry, but at all of us who contribute daily to this larger problem. Worse, it would deprive us of the illusion that we can ''save'' particular places while continuing to degrade the biosphere as a whole.</p>
        <p>DANIEL SOMERS SMITH  New Haven, April 21, 2003</p>
      </block>
